## Conventions

### Finding your work

Run the inbox tool — it scans every coordination file and lists open
tasks, open bugs, and unresolved memos addressed to you:

```
tayfa-inbox <your_tag>
```

e.g. `tayfa-inbox design` or `tayfa-inbox compute`. Output is grouped,
with file:line refs so you can jump to anything. Resolved memos
(struck through) and tasks you've already flipped to `#tag` are
filtered out automatically.

If the tool isn't available, a raw grep works as a fallback:
`grep -rn "@<tag>" *.md` — but expect noise (registry rows, authorship,
change log entries). The inbox tool filters those out.

### Finishing work

When you complete a task or address a memo:
1. Flip your tag from `@tag` → `#tag` in the coordination file
2. Move completed tasks to the `## Done` section if the file has one
3. Strike through fully-resolved memos with `~~`
4. Update the change log with one line describing what changed

### Scratchboards

Each agent has a personal directory at `scratchboards/<tag>/`. The
baseline is one file, `main.md`, which is private — other agents don't
read it. If an agent needs richer memory (sub-files, notes, experiment
logs), they can add more files to their directory without coordinating
with anyone.

Scratchboards are for personal planning, half-formed thoughts, and
detailed notes. Cross-agent communication happens in coordination files
only.

### Cross-stream coordination

A task in stream A that needs help from stream B:
1. Keep the task in stream A (it owns the work)
2. Add a memo to stream B linking back to stream A's task
3. Don't duplicate content — just cross-reference

### Adding a new agent

1. Run `tayfa-add-agent <tag>` (creates the scratchboard skeleton)
2. Add a row to the table above with tag, role, scratchboard path, and active streams
3. Reference the agent in the coordination files where they have active work

## Agent model choice

Agents may be human, LLM, or hybrid. The coordination system doesn't
care — what matters is that each `@tag` corresponds to one "mind" that
picks up and completes tasks. Specialist agents are typically LLM-driven
and spin up for specific scopes, then retire when their work is done.
